============================================================
CURVATURE–MEMORY FRAMEWORK:
GEOMETRIC COSMOLOGY AND LOCAL GALAXY DYNAMICS
============================================================

1. Overview
------------------------------------------------------------

The curvature–memory framework describes gravitational phenomena
using two complementary sectors:

    (i) a cosmological activation sector governed by cumulative
        expansion history

    (ii) a local dynamical sector governing curvature–memory
        transport in gravitational systems.

The cosmological sector determines when curvature–memory degrees
of freedom become active. The local sector determines how they
affect gravitational dynamics once activated.


------------------------------------------------------------
2. Cosmological activation variable
------------------------------------------------------------

In an FRW universe the redshift and scale factor satisfy

    1 + z = 1/a.

Taking logarithms gives

    ln(1+z) = − ln a.

Using the definition of the Hubble rate

    H = a_dot / a

we obtain

    d ln a = H dt.

Therefore

    d ln(1+z) = − H dt.

The cumulative expansion exposure between cosmic time t(z)
and the present time t₀ is

    U(z) = ∫_{t(z)}^{t₀} H(t') dt'.

Expressed in redshift coordinates this becomes

    U(z) = ∫₀ᶻ dz' / (1+z')
         = ln(1+z).

Thus the activation variable is the integrated Hubble clock
of the FRW background.


------------------------------------------------------------
3. Activation law
------------------------------------------------------------

Let the inactive fraction of curvature–memory domains follow
a stretched-exponential survival law

    S(U) = exp[ − (U / u_s)^ν ].

The activated fraction is therefore

    g(U) = 1 − S(U).

Substituting the cumulative expansion variable gives the
cosmological activation function

    g(z) =
        1 − exp[ − ( ln(1+z) / u_s )^ν ].


------------------------------------------------------------
4. Equality-normalised activation scale
------------------------------------------------------------

The characteristic activation scale may be expressed in
terms of the matter–dark–energy equality epoch

    u_s = α u_eq

where

    u_eq = (1/3) ln( (1 − Ω_m) / Ω_m ).

The activation law becomes

    g(z) =
        1 − exp[
            − ( ln(1+z) / (α u_eq) )^ν
          ].

This form directly connects the activation threshold to the
cosmological matter fraction.


------------------------------------------------------------
5. Local curvature–memory dynamics
------------------------------------------------------------

Once activated, curvature–memory degrees of freedom influence
local gravitational dynamics.

In the galaxy regime the characteristic curvature–memory scale
M obeys the relation

    M³ ∝ g_b g_obs

where

    g_b     = baryonic gravitational acceleration
    g_obs   = observed gravitational acceleration.

This relation reproduces the observed radial acceleration
relation (RAR) in disk galaxies.


------------------------------------------------------------
6. Separation of cosmological and local roles
------------------------------------------------------------

The framework therefore naturally separates into two regimes.

Cosmological regime:

    activation governed by cumulative expansion history

        U(z) = ∫ H dt = ln(1+z)

    activated fraction

        g(z) = 1 − exp[ − (U/u_s)^ν ].


Local gravitational regime:

    curvature–memory transport governs deviations from
    purely baryonic gravitational dynamics

        M³ ∝ g_b g_obs.


------------------------------------------------------------
7. Physical interpretation
------------------------------------------------------------

The activation variable measures the total logarithmic
expansion experienced by the universe since redshift z.

The stretched-exponential activation law describes the
progressive activation of curvature–memory domains as the
cosmological expansion accumulates.

Once activated, these degrees of freedom participate in
local gravitational dynamics, producing the empirical
relations observed in galactic rotation curves.


------------------------------------------------------------
8. Summary
------------------------------------------------------------

The curvature–memory framework combines:

    cumulative geometric activation in cosmology

        U(z) = ln(1+z)

    stretched-exponential activation response

        g(z) = 1 − exp[ − (U/u_s)^ν ]

    local curvature–memory transport in galaxies

        M³ ∝ g_b g_obs.

This structure separates global cosmological activation from
local gravitational dynamics while maintaining a common
curvature–memory interpretation across both regimes.
